Pestilence Fire<br>
By R. G. Faulkner<br>
<br>
The ground shuddered like an old woman warding off the chill of a winter morning, and then all was still.  Not a sound could be heard; not the wind that slowly rustled the leaves of the great stand of Birch trees that lie just yards beyond the great crater that suddenly appeared.  Nor the birds that chirped only moments before from within them.  The trees were smoldering and leafless; stripped and singed by a great blast.  Nothing stirred or moved except for a young man that lay on his stomach inside the immense bowl.  His arms flailed and his hands fought loose, blackened dirt for handholds as he struggled to drag himself to the top.  Suddenly, as he reached the very crest, he stopped moving.   He hung there just on the periphery, motionless.  He appeared dead.  <br>
<br>
“Dureck!”  The scream cut through the silence. “Dureck!”<br>
<br>
Leana ran up and reached down to him, placing a hand on each shoulder.  She began to tug franticly, fighting desperately with his weight to pull him up and out of the pit.  With each tug, the dirt released great wafts of sulfur and pitch that flooded her nostrils with an urgent need to sneeze and turn away.  She resisted the urge and fought desperately to maintain a foothold while struggling with the dead weight that was her closest friend. “Why do you have to be so heavy?”  Finally, she got him up over the crown and rolled him onto his back.  She was met by a broad smile on an ashen, black face.  He did not move and his open eyes seemed to stare far away into the nothingness of the beyond.  <br>
<br>
Her gasp was filled with panic and horror.  “Oh dear Maker.  Oh lord.”  She reached into her pack and quickly found a cloth.  Drenching it with water, she began to delicately wipe away the ash and soot that painted him.  With each wipe she exposed pink, bubbled skin.  Her hand began to shake uncontrollably as each touch sparked fear in her cleansing strokes.  “You stubborn mule.”  She cried, unable to control the emotion of seeing him in this state.  “Blasted fool, look at you.  We told you, didn’t we?  But you had to try, didn’t you?  You couldn’t listen to us.  Now…” she hesitated and closed her eyes.  “Now look at you.”  She slammed her hand into his chest and then pulled him up into her arms and began to sob.<br>
  <br>
“Why must you always be so dramatic?” Leana heard the voice come strolling from beyond the trees towards her.  It was emotionless and carefree, as if it had not heard or seen the giant explosion or the great column of fire that had flung itself to the heavens.  Almost as if it was unable to see now the cavernous depression it approached or smell the suffocating stench of burnt soil that permeated the air.  Leana felt herself flush with anger.<br>
<br>
“Get over here and help me, demon wraith.”  She could not hide her emotions.<br>
<br>
“Is he alive?”  His words were full of unconcern.<br>
<br>
“You’re the healer.  You tell me.  Is this the face of someone alive?”<br>
<br>
She watched Marthis bend down and check him closely.  His pale hand touched the hot, pink skin and pulled back quickly as if pricked by a thorn.  He let his hand get a little closer and then slowly traced the outline of Dureck’s face and worked toward his chest, hovering there as if it was searching for some sign.  She looked up at Marthis’ eyes seeking desperately for confirmation of her greatest fear.  They were closed.<br>
<br>
He sighed.<br>
<br>
She choked.  “Is he alive?”  She stood and turned away needing to hide her emotions from Marthis.<br>
<br>
“Yes,” he said.  “Do you know the jukingail plant?”  <br>
<br>
She turned back around. “The red leaved bush with the pinkish berries?”<br>
<br>
“Yes.  Gather me two handfuls of the berries.  I’ll make a salve.  Look at his hands.”  <br>
<br>
She looked down to see the backsides of his hands were completely filled with the blistering of burnt flesh.  Taking them in her own, she gasped as she turned them over and saw the black flesh that was his palms; charred and cracked exposing whitish-pink flesh underneath what used to be skin.  Her eyes filled with horror.<br>
<br>
“Oh lord, his hands are ruined.  How will he”<br>
<br>
“Go get the jukingail.  Hurry.  We have little time.”<br>
<br>
