<br>
Dureck opened his eyes.  <br>
<br>
“Where am I,” he said.  Dureck’s eyes were filled with the images of a white cloud.   He closed his eyes and opened them.  Again, it was the same haunting white world of nothing.  A hand grasped his arm and pulled it back just before he could reach up to rub his eyes.  Working his eyes back and forth in the cloud, he could find no images, not even a blurry figure.  He tried to get up.  The hand pushed him back down.<br>
<br>
“Shh, save your strength.”<br>
<br>
Then he remembered and knew what the white cloud was.  “Leana?  Leana!  Dear lords, I can’t see.  Leana where are you?”    He reached out frantically trying to feel her in the white world.<br>
<br>
“I said be quiet.”  Her hand touched him gingerly on his chest keeping him down on the soft bedding.  “You’ve been hurt.  We have been at it for days trying to heal you.  We were afraid you were…” Leana’s words were filled with agony.  “Marthis is resting.  Soon as he wakes I will have him look at you.”  The bed shifted and creaked as she leaned over and kissed him on his forehead.<br>
<br>
“I can’t see.  Lord’s Maker I can’t see.”<br>
<br>
“Your sight will return,” she said.  Her voice was just a whisper.  He could feel her warm breath right next to his ear.  Hints of vanilla filled his nose as her hair brushed up against his face.  Never before did she smell this way, and nothing before smelled purer or sweeter.  He imagined her impish smile as she whispered into his ear.  Somehow it calmed him.<br>
<br>
“Where am I?”  He felt her hand come to his own, and he suddenly realized it was bandaged.  He felt the other, which was also bandaged.  <br>
<br>
“Dlislendoor.”<br>
<br>
“Back in Dlislendoor?  Why!”  He struggled with the realization.  He was back where he started and once again far from Kelnfarl and the Moord.   But why?  Dureck fought with all his might to sit up, but his strength was sapped and the hand pushed a little firmer holding him down.<br>
<br>
“I said save your strength.”  Dureck knew she meant it.  Her snapped orders always cut like a filet knife when she was angry.<br>
<br>
“Why?  Why come all this way back?  We have to stop Vendimack.  It’s almost solstice.”  Dureck felt a tugging from inside him.  Something snatched away his last bit of remaining strength.  Within seconds his white world faded to black and he was fast asleep.<br>
