<br>
“There will be time for that later.  Now he must rest.  That’s all that matters if he’s to recover.”  Leana watched Marthis stand and shuffle his clothes.  “How long was I asleep?” he said.<br>
<br>
“Most of the day.  It’s near supper.”<br>
<br>
Marthis frowned.  “Why did you not wake me when I asked?”<br>
<br>
“You’ll do him no good if you’re not rested.”<br>
<br>
“I’ll do him less good if he’s dead.”<br>
<br>
“Dureck is strong.  Already he recovers.  It’s the way of Martwood men.  But he needs your skills Marthis and because of that I let you sleep.  You’ll do him better, rested.”  She watched Marthis fume.  Leana rarely won their arguments and disagreements.  She despised the foul man’s interference: always with an opinion, always meddling, always filling his head with words of adventure and glory, and always putting Dureck in the path of danger.<br>
<br>
“Woman, I know what is best.  From now on” <br>
<br>
In a flash of surprising speed, Leana pulled a knife and quickly brought it up to Marthis’ throat.<br>
<br>
“Demon wraith, I have a little secret that I think it’s time you understood.”  Leana leaned in closer as she moved to his side.  “You do not command me.  And not Vendimack himself can stop me where Dureck is concerned.  Never forget that.  What I do only concerns him.  Your influence over Dureck has led him to this.  For that I hold you personally responsible.”  She walked behind him.  The dagger never faltered as she moved.  It hung there at the edge of this throat.  She knew with one flick of her wrist it would slice through his artery and he would die in minutes unable to do anything to stop the act.  She wished he would try to move.<br>
<br>
“Leana…”<br>
<br>
“I would watch my tongue, wraith.  Dureck is my charge and my only friend.  You will fix what you have done to him, and you will see that soon he is as healthy as the day we walked out of here three weeks ago.  You got him into this.  I am going to get him out.  But first, I regret, I need you.  You’ll fix the mess you’ve made and then you’ll leave.  If anything happens to Dureck that upsets me, you’ll find yourself lying in a puddle of black wraith blood.”  <br>
<br>
Marthis started to say something.  She could see he was tensing up, the anger getting to him.  Before he could speak she leaned in closer so that only he could hear her next words.  Her mouth was just inches from his ear.  “If you ever know one thing, know this demon wraith; Makfadi do not play games.”  She felt Marthis gulp.<br>
<br>
“I must see to him,” was all he said.<br>
<br>
She let the dagger drop away and watched as Marthis rubbed at his throat as he walked over to Dureck’s bedside.  He never took an eye off her.  She could live with that.<br>
<br>
“Could he see?”<br>
<br>
“No,” she said.<br>
<br>
“I was afraid of that.  Well, time will heal the blindness.  The affradin never lasts.”<br>
<br>
“And how would you know about the Affradin?  Seen it before have we?  How many other men have you seen blinded, demon wraith?  How many suffered so that you could discover the magic of that cursed metal?”  She was getting angry again: his tone and mannerism were insulting, as if everything was simple and calculating.  He played to easily with other’s lives.<br>
<br>
“Leana, perhaps you should get some rest.  I’ve a lot to do and you are exhausted.”  She knew he was only trying to get rid of her.  But he was right.  The exhaustion of the past week’s ordeal was catching up with her.  As much as she mistrusted him, she had watched him work for two days nonstop to save him.  He had used his magic and his skill, and Dureck had improved.  Marthis drained himself in those two day, to the point that she had been forced to carry his sleeping shell into the bed after he had collapsed.  For some reason, she knew he wished Dureck no harm.  At least not now.<br>
<br>
“I’ll be in my room.  Wake me if he comes to or if anything changes.”  She started for the door.<br>
<br>
“Leana, there is something else.  Something you should know.  Something that I think would be of interest to your health.”  She turned to see him smiling at her with that look of indifferent arrogance.  She felt her blood go cold as a flash of light went off in the room.  She could not move her arms.  She could not speak.<br>
<br>
Marthis walked over next to her and leaned into her so that only she could hear his words.  “Raise one of your tainted daggers again to my throat and I will see that your arm is ripped from your body before you get it halfway.  Vendimack is my only concern, and Dureck.  Interfere with that, and you’ll find yourself next to all your Makfadi sisters, rotting in hell.”  Leana looked at his eyes.  They were red with hatred.<br>
<br>
She gulped.<br>
